1.5 Share insights from the initial data analysis¶

In [16]:
def hist_plot(df):

    list_cols = df.columns
    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(nrows=4, ncols=3, figsize=(15,10))
    ax1 = ax1.flatten()
    for i, col in enumerate(list_cols):
        ax = sns.histplot(df[col], ax=ax1[i], kde = True, color = '#095899')
        ax.set_xlabel(col, fontsize=12, fontweight = 'bold')
        ax.set_ylabel("Count", fontsize=12, fontweight = 'bold')
        ax.tick_params(axis='x', labelsize=10)
        ax.tick_params(axis='y', labelsize=10)
    plt.tight_layout()

# one hot encoding the target class as it is a muliclass classification problem
# converting target to one hot encoded vectors
# Adjust the class labels to be zero-based
y_train_adjusted = y_train -3
y_test_adjusted = y_test -3

# Perform one-hot encoding with num_classes=6 (total unique classes after adjustment)
y_train_cat = tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(y_train_adjusted,num_classes=6)
y_test_cat = tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(y_test_adjusted, num_classes=6)

model = Sequential([Input(shape=(11,)),
                   Dense(64, activation='relu'),  
                   Dense(32, activation='relu'), 
                   Dense(6, activation='softmax')])

from tensorflow.keras.initializers import HeUniform

                   Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal'), 
                   tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.05), BatchNormalization(momentum = 0.5),   
                   Dense(32, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal'), 
                   tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.05), BatchNormalization(momentum = 0.5),   
                   Dense(32, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal'), 
                   Dense(6, activation='softmax')])
